{% raw %}
  newsletter.inky.liquid — an inky template that is ALSO a real Liquid
  template.

  NOTE ON THIS COMMENT'S OWN SYNTAX: this header is wrapped in Liquid's
  raw-block tag pair (see this file's very first and very last lines),
  not an HTML <!-- --> comment and not Liquid's comment-block tag,
  precisely because the prose below needs to quote literal {{ }} / {% %}
  syntax as examples, INCLUDING a nested for/endfor pair. An HTML comment
  doesn't work: Liquid's lexer does not treat HTML comments as inert, it
  tokenizes the entire file regardless of surrounding HTML, so a literal
  "{% %}" inside an HTML comment is still parsed as a real (invalid) tag.
  Liquid's comment-block tag doesn't work either, empirically: it still
  parses nested block structure while swallowing its body, so a nested,
  unbalanced-looking for/endfor pair quoted as prose inside one raised a
  "tag was never closed" parse error. The raw-block tag pair wrapping
  this whole header is Liquid's actual "everything until the literal
  matching closing marker, no tokenizing at all" construct — the same
  role Twig's {# #} plays in the PHP original. (Note, for the same
  reason, that this prose avoids spelling out the raw-block's own
  literal opening/closing tokens by name anywhere in the middle of this
  block — writing the real closing token here would end the block
  early, mid-sentence, which is exactly the bug this paragraph is
  describing.) It's discarded before <layout> the same
  way ordinary text would be (see inky-core's layout-prefix-trimming: it
  discards everything before the <layout> tag regardless of what that
  content is), so this block vanishes from the output in both orders
  exactly like the PHP original's {# #} does.

  ENGINE SUBSTITUTION NOTE (Ruby port of SUITE.md's 10-twig-cms): the PHP
  reference suite uses Twig, integrating inky into the shape a Twig-based
  CMS (Total CMS) takes. Twig has no Ruby port. Liquid is the pragmatic
  Jinja-family substitute here — same {{ }}/{% %} delimiter family, same
  filter-pipe syntax, same whitespace-control dashes, and (like the Twig
  build here, which explicitly sets autoescape => false) no HTML
  autoescaping by default, so the two orders below stay directly
  comparable to their PHP counterparts. The two-orders + timing +
  recipient-1-equality SHAPE below is the actual point of this example,
  not which engine renders it — see run.rb's own header comment for the
  Ruby-specific write-up filed in port-ruby-report.md.

  This is a CMS-integrator note, written for someone wiring inky into a
  Liquid-capable CMS: this file mixes inky's own tags (<layout>,
  <container>, <raw>, ...) with real Liquid syntax ({{ }}, {% %},
  filters). There are two valid orders to combine them — see run.rb one
  level up, which builds both, times them, and asserts they agree for one
  recipient.

  This file lives inside emails/ — the self-contained base_path run.rb
  passes to Inky.build (see emails/layouts/main.html for the base-root
  resolution rule this whole tree follows: every src/href below is
  root-relative, with no parent-directory traversal, regardless of which
  file references it).

  ORDER A — Liquid first, then inky (Inky.build, no data: option). Liquid
  renders the FULL document — substituting every {{ }} and expanding the
  {% for %} loop below — before inky ever sees it; inky then only does
  component transform, SCSS, and CSS inlining. Simple, always correct,
  but costs a full inky build PER RECIPIENT.

  ORDER B — inky first (the CMS fast path), then Liquid per recipient.
  Inky.build runs ONCE, with no data: option, on this raw file — all
  Liquid syntax passes through untouched (inky's own MiniJinja merge step
  is simply skipped when data: isn't passed; see 03-data-merge). That one
  build does layout/include resolution, component transform, and CSS
  inlining a single time, producing a "shell" that still contains literal
  Liquid syntax — cache THAT instead of re-doing the inky build for every
  recipient. Liquid then renders the cached shell per recipient, which is
  far cheaper than a full inky build per recipient. This is the shape a
  CMS wants: template content changes rarely, recipients don't.

  THE <raw> RULE — and here it stops being optional, unlike the
  defense-in-depth framing in 03-data-merge's comment. In Order B, the
  {% for %} loop below has NOT been expanded yet when inky's HTML5-based
  component transform runs over this file. A bare, un-wrapped
  {% for %}...{% endfor %} sitting directly inside <table> (outside any
  <tr>) is, as far as the HTML5 parser is concerned, stray non-table
  text — the spec's foster-parenting rule relocates it OUT of the table
  entirely, silently detaching the loop from the rows it's meant to
  produce and corrupting the newsletter for every recipient. (Order A
  never hits this: by the time inky sees the document, Liquid has already
  expanded the loop into ordinary <tr> tags, which ARE valid table
  content and are never foster-parented.) <raw> sidesteps the problem
  because inky extracts <raw>...</raw> content BEFORE html5ever parses
  anything at all, replacing it with an HTML COMMENT placeholder —
  comments, unlike bare text, are legal directly inside <table>, so the
  placeholder survives parsing exactly where it was, and the real
  (untouched) content is spliced back in afterward. One thing NOT to draw
  from this: <raw> content is re-injected before CSS inlining runs, so it
  is NOT invisible to the inliner. The product rows below carry explicit
  style="" attributes for a different reason — THIS example builds with
  inline_css: false (see the CSS INLINING CONSTRAINT section below), so
  no per-tag styles are inlined for anything in this document, and the
  rows have to style themselves.

  TWO MORE REAL QUIRKS THIS EXAMPLE HAD TO WORK AROUND, found empirically
  while building the PHP original and reproduced here — all worth knowing
  if you hit unexplained diffs between your own Order A/B outputs:

  1. {%- for product in products -%} / {%- endfor -%} use Liquid's
     explicit whitespace-control dashes, and the loop body is written
     densely (no stray blank lines). Without the dashes, indentation
     written around those two tags leaks into the loop body's own
     leading/trailing text once Liquid expands it, and — because Order A
     normalizes whitespace AFTER Liquid has expanded the loop into 3 rows,
     while Order B normalizes the ONE-row shell BEFORE Liquid ever
     duplicates it — that leakage isn't cleaned up the same way in both
     orders. The dashes make the loop body's own whitespace fully explicit
     instead of relying on default trimming heuristics.

  2. Even with that, inky's pipeline-level cleanup (break_long_lines /
     collapse_closing_tags in inky-core's pipeline.rs) inserts or folds
     newlines around every <table>/<tbody>/<tr>/<td>/<th> tag it finds,
     unconditionally, in whatever document is in front of it at the moment
     it runs. Order A runs that cleanup on the FULLY-EXPANDED 3-row
     document; Order B runs it ONCE on the 1-row shell, and Liquid's later
     per-recipient duplication has no further inky pass to reconcile the
     seams between copies. The visible symptom is a whitespace-only
     difference in the padding directly between table tags at row
     boundaries — never in the rows' actual content. run.rb's equality
     check normalizes exactly that (and only that) before comparing — see
     the comment there for why that's principled and not a cop-out.

  CSS INLINING CONSTRAINT — both builds (Order A and Order B) must use
  inline_css: false. CSS inlining runs a separate HTML5 parse over inky's
  component-transform output. At shell-build time (Order B), the <raw>-
  wrapped loop remains literal {% for %}/{% endfor %} text sitting beside a
  <tr> inside <tbody>. That second parse's foster-parenting rules relocate
  bare template text out of the table, the same failure mode that <raw>
  prevents during the first parse. Setting inline_css: false sidesteps the
  second parse entirely, keeping both orders byte-comparable (framework_css
  still ships the compiled theme as a <style> block). See run.rb's comment
  for the full detail. This constraint does not apply to templates that
  merge all data before inky runs (see 09-transactional, which uses
  inline_css: true).

  Inky's OWN data: option (see 03-data-merge, 09-transactional) speaks a
  MiniJinja dialect that is syntax-compatible with Liquid for the simple
  cases used here — {{ var }}, {% if %}, {% for %} mean the same thing to
  both engines. Reach for data: alone when a template only needs that.
  Reach for real Liquid, as here, when you need something a CMS's own
  Liquid environment already provides that data: can't: filters, tags,
  custom drops, template inheritance. The loyalty_badge filter below
  (registered in Ruby, in run.rb, via Liquid::Environment#register_filter)
  is a genuinely Liquid-only feature — inky's data merge has no mechanism
  for user-registered filters at all. (Twig's built-in |upper became
  Liquid's built-in |upcase below — same idea, different engine's stdlib
  spelling; this is the one filter-name change this port needed to make
  beyond the engine substitution itself.)
{% endraw %}
<layout src="layouts/main.html" title="This week at Northwind Coffee">
<link rel="stylesheet" href="themes/northwind.scss">
<container>
  <row>
    <column lg="12">
      <h1>Hey {{ subscriber.first_name }}, here's what's roasting</h1>
      <p>{{ subscriber.tier | loyalty_badge }} members get first pick of this
      week's small-batch arrivals before we open the list to everyone
      else.</p>
      <table role="presentation" width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
        <tr>
          <th align="left">New arrival</th>
          <th align="right">Price</th>
        </tr>
<raw>
{%- for product in products -%}
<tr>
<td style="padding:8px 0;">{{ product.name | upcase }}</td>
<td align="right" style="padding:8px 0;">${{ product.price }}</td>
</tr>
{%- endfor -%}
</raw>
</table>
      <button href="{{ shop_url }}">Shop this week's arrivals</button>
    </column>
  </row>
</container>
